Provider
The Provider component keeps an instance of the store and provides it to all nested Consumer components.
Props



Property
Type
Description




initialState
(any?)
An initial state unique to this Provider instance. It overwrites the global model.



Example
import { createStore } from &apos;alveron&apos;

const model = 0
const actions = {
  increment: state =&gt; state + 1,
  decrement: state =&gt; state - 1
}

const { Provider } = createStore({
  actions,
  model
})

const Counter = () =&gt; (
  &lt;Provider&gt;
    ...
  &lt;/Provider&gt;
)

Using initialState
The following example with start the counter from 10 instead of 0.
const StartFrom10 = () =&gt; (
  &lt;Provider initialState={10}&gt;
    ...
  &lt;/Provider&gt;
)

docs/api/Consumer.html.body:
Consumer
The Consumer component is used to access  state, actions and effects from the closest Provider component.
It provides a render-prop interface that passes a single object containing state, actions and effects to the render function.

It must be wrapped by at least one Provider component or else it throws an error.

Example
import { createStore } from &apos;alveron&apos;

const model = 0
const actions = {
  increment: state =&gt; state + 1,
  decrement: state =&gt; state - 1
}

const { Provider, Consumer } = createStore({
  actions,
  model
})

const Counter = () =&gt; (
  &lt;Provider&gt;
    &lt;Consumer&gt;
      {({ state, actions }) =&gt; (
        &lt;div&gt;
          &lt;div&gt;Counter: {state}&lt;/div&gt;
          &lt;button onClick={actions.increment}&gt;+&lt;/button&gt;
          &lt;button onClick={actions.decrement}&gt;-&lt;/button&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
      )}
    &lt;/Consumer&gt;
  &lt;/Provider&gt;
)

docs/api/Wrapper.html.body:
Wrapper
Wrapper is just a convenient component that combines both Provider and Consumer into a single component.
It helps to keep your component tree clean when using local state.
It accepts all props that Provider and Consumer accept and requires a render function passed as children.
Example
import { createStore } from &apos;alveron&apos;

const model = 0
const actions = {
  increment: state =&gt; state + 1,
  decrement: state =&gt; state - 1
}

const { Wrapper } = createStore({
  actions,
  model
})

const Counter = ({ defaultCount }) =&gt; (
  &lt;Wrapper&gt;
    {({ state, actions }) =&gt; (
      &lt;div&gt;
        &lt;div&gt;Counter: {state}&lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;button onClick={actions.increment}&gt;+&lt;/button&gt;
        &lt;button onClick={actions.decrement}&gt;-&lt;/button&gt;
      &lt;/div&gt;
    )}
  &lt;/Wrapper&gt;
)

docs/api/useAlveron.html.body:
useAlveron

Note: Using the hooks API requires react @16.7.0-alpha.1 or @16.7.0-alpha.2.

The createStore equivalent using the React hooks API.It uses useState under the hood and can be considered just a small abstraction layer over basic hooks.    
It accepts the same options and returns the same interface. 
Options



Argument
Type
Description




actions
(Object?)
A map of actions where the key represents the action name and the value represents the action reducer


effects
(Object?)
A map of effects where the key represents the effect name and the value represents the updater


model
(any?)
The default model reflecting the initial state shape



Returns
(Object) an object containing the state, actions and effects to be used inside a React component.
Example
import { useAlveron } from &apos;alveron&apos;

const model = 0
const actions = {
  increment: state =&gt; state + 1,
  decrement: state =&gt; state - 1
}

function Counter() {
  const { state, actions } = useAlveron({ 
    model, 
    actions 
  })

  return (
    &lt;div&gt;
      &lt;h1&gt;{state}&lt;/h1&gt;
      &lt;button onClick={increment}&gt;+&lt;/button&gt;
      &lt;button onClick={decrement}&gt;-&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  )
}
